Dr. Shuai. ZHANG, A.K.A. Sjaak by his Dutch colleagues, born in 1984 in Qingdao, Shandong, China; LL.B and LL.M obtained from China University of Political Science and Law (CUPL), PhD in Law obtained from Utrecht University (UU) in the Netherlands; financed by China Scholarship Council (CSC), he departed for the Netherlands in 2012 to further his legal study involving comparative criminal (procedure) law, supervised by Prof. John Vervaele, president of AIDP, Prof. Chrisje Brants, leading expert in the field of comparative criminal procedure, and Prof. He Jiahong, leading expert in Chinese criminal (procedure) law, culminating in a PhD degree in 2017. Currently serving as global partner of Shanghai Duan&Duan Law Firm, guest researcher of Utrecht Law School.  

Served as judge assistant respectively in 1st Civil Division of the People's Court of Shibei District, Qingdao, 2nd Criminal Division of the Intermediate People's Court of Qingdao, 1st Criminal Division of Shandong High People's Court, and 5th Criminal Division of the Supreme People's Court of China, and concomitantly insightful into the entire chain of processes in Chinese criminal trials. Acquired his “Legal Professional Qualification Certificate” in 2009, and started his practice in Qingdao from the year 2010 onward, specializing in defense of various kinds of criminal cases, especially of those involving severe punishments or even death penalty; served as the defense counsel of B. Liu, one of the perpetrators in a high-profile human trafficking case reported by China Central Television, culminating in a satisfying outcome; 
 
During his stay in the Netherlands, he spared time to provide legal aids and gratis lectures to Chinese immigrants and students, as well as cross-border dispute resolution to relevant companies or individuals; now undertaking a joint research project by UU, Zhejiang University and Alibaba regarding Comprehensive Regulation of the Internet ecology (cross-border online arbitration).

My mission is to enable burdened and/or stuck clients to unburden and liberate themselves. This entails honest self-exploration and self-confrontation, as well as positive transformation of key aspects of their 'inner world' (the psyche and personality) that have been 'frozen', immobile, lacking vitality and thus holding them back. Typically, these are manifest as self-limiting cognitions and self-sabotaging behaviours, and/or conflicts between personality parts, and/or unhealed emotional wounds (trauma).
   My working principles are equality, mutual respect, non-violent communication, empathy and compassion.
   In working with clients, I am inevitably confronted by my limitations, blind spots and, sometimes, false assumptions. However, I have come to realise that 'failure' is illusory: limitations, blind spots and false assumptions, once consciously realised, are just opportunities to learn and grow.
   Guiding personal change requires a client-centred approach and a therapeutic attitude of patient inquisitiveness, respect and empathy. Each individual is unique and special, so standard treatment protocols are inappropriate. For each new client, a new therapy unfolds naturally when the therapist trusts the process -- to which empathy is crucial -- and encourages the client to take ownership of, and full responsibility for, his/her problems, to set his/her own goals and to take concrete steps towards them.
  The practice is a non-judgmental listening space, because curiosity and discovery end as soon as judging starts. Judgment drives disconnection; empathy creates connnection. Each client is unique and special and deserves warm understanding, unconditional empathy and excellent care.

The keys to success of therapy are:
1. Seeing that each 'problem' is actually an opportunity;
2. Realising that 'negative' emotions are messengers that have come to tell us about our unmet needs;
3. Cultivating "witnessing presence" (as defined by Eckhart Tolle in 'The Power of Now');
4. Being "a heart with ears" (as envisioned by the late Dr Marshall B. Rosenberg);
5. Encouraging open, creative thinking and imagining, unconditional self-empathy, and excellent self-care;
6. Mobilising the innate wisdom and self-healing power of the human psyche.

None of this would have been possible without Hans Knibbe, Pieter van Dijk, Edwin Königel, Karen te Pas, Wim Bresser, Erik Ivo Homan, Hans van der Esch, Michelle Dusseldorp, Rita Gras & Cathelijne Veenkamp. There are no words to express my gratitude to you, my patient, empathetic, wise guides and role-models.

I hold a bachelor's degree in English Language and Literature and an MA degree in Linguistic and Literary Studies from the Federal University of Santa Catarina, Brazil. In the Netherlands, I have completed a Research Master's degree in Literary Studies at Leiden University. At present, I am a PhD candidate at the Centre for the Arts in Society at Leiden University. My research interests encompass Literature, Cultural Studies, and Cinema with great concern for Post-structuralist approaches, namely, Gender studies, Masculinities, Schizoanalysis, Intersectionality, and Postcolonial theory.

Apart from my scholarly activities, I have been working as an English and Drama teacher. I hold ample experience with different teaching environments and methodological approaches. Through my practice, I seek to achieve the following objectives:
• To provide a safe space for educational and subjective experimentation;
• To cultivate critical thinking;
• To foment students’ epistemological curiosity.

The Ministerie van Onderwijs, Cultuur en Wetenschap granted me Eerstegraads Lesbevoegdheid in 2021.
